# üèóÔ∏è Domain 2Ô∏è‚É£ ‚Äî Software Solution Architecture

This domain defines **how systems are designed** and **how all components (DB, server, code, integrations) communicate securely and efficiently**.

---

## üß± Typical Enterprise Java Stack Architecture

```
User ‚Üí Apache HTTPD ‚Üí WebLogic/JBoss/Tomcat (App layer)
           ‚Üì
        REST APIs (Spring Boot, JAX-RS)
           ‚Üì
     Service Layer (Business Logic)
           ‚Üì
     DAO Layer (JPA/Hibernate, PL/SQL)
           ‚Üì
     Database (Oracle, MySQL, Redis, MongoDB)
           ‚Üì
     CI/CD ‚Üí Jenkins ‚Üí AWS EC2/ECS
```

---

### üîπ Core Technologies Used:

| Layer              | Technology                            | Purpose                       |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| **Presentation**   | Angular / React / JSP                 | Frontend UI                   |
| **API Layer**      | Spring Boot / Jakarta EE              | RESTful endpoints             |
| **Business Layer** | Java 17, Spring Core, Design Patterns | Implements core logic         |
| **Persistence**    | JPA/Hibernate, PL/SQL                 | ORM and stored procedures     |
| **Database**       | Oracle, MySQL, MongoDB, Redis         | Relational + NoSQL mix        |
| **App Servers**    | WebLogic, JBoss, Tomcat               | Deployment/runtime containers |
| **Integration**    | JMS, Kafka, Web Services              | Cross-system communication    |
| **Cloud Infra**    | AWS EC2, S3, Lambda, RDS              | Elastic deployment            |
| **CI/CD**          | Jenkins + Maven + GitHub              | Automation                    |
| **Security**       | Fortify, NexusIQ, WebInspect          | Code and dependency scanning  |

---

## üß† Example: Secure Payment Microservice Architecture

```
[Client UI]
   |
   v
[API Gateway] ‚Üí Validates JWT Token
   |
   v
[Payment Service (Spring Boot)]
   |- Business Logic (Service Layer)
   |- JPA Repositories (DAO Layer)
   |- Redis Cache (Low-latency lookups)
   |- MongoDB for transactions log
   |
   v
[Oracle DB] ‚Üí PL/SQL Stored Procedures
```

**Security Layers:**

* OAuth2 / JWT authentication
* HTTPS-only transport
* HP Fortify scans for static vulnerabilities
* NexusIQ scans for vulnerable dependencies
* WebInspect for dynamic (runtime) testing

---

### üß± Example: Spring Boot + Redis + Oracle + AWS

**application.properties**

```properties
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@dbhost:1521:prod
spring.datasource.username=secure_user
spring.datasource.password=${DB_PASSWORD}
spring.cache.type=redis
spring.redis.host=redis-prod.internal
aws.s3.bucket=secure-docs
```

**Service Layer Example**

```java
@Service
public class DocumentService {

    @Autowired private RedisTemplate<String, Document> redis;
    @Autowired private DocumentRepository repository;
    @Autowired private AmazonS3 s3;

    public Document getDocument(String docId) {
        return redis.opsForValue().get(docId);
    }

    public void uploadDocument(MultipartFile file) {
        String key = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
        s3.putObject("secure-docs", key, file.getInputStream(), new ObjectMetadata());
        repository.save(new Document(key, file.getOriginalFilename()));
    }
}
```

This combines **Spring Boot**, **Redis caching**, **Oracle persistence**, and **AWS S3** integration ‚Äî a very typical real-world enterprise setup.

